He was an Academician of the Russian Academy of Sciences (RAN) since 2016, having been a corresponding member since 1997, and was a member of the Bureau of the Department of Physiological Sciences of RAN. From 1990 to 2017, he served as the director of the Institute of Human Brain of the Russian Academy of Sciences.

Медведев specialized in neurophysiology and psychophysiology, with scientific interests including the healthy and diseased human brain, altered states of consciousness, brain mapping, obsessive states, and the psychophysiology of meditations. He was born into a family of physiologists, with his mother being Natalya Petrovna Bekhtereva and his father Vsevolod Ivanovich Medvedev. He received his doctorate in biological sciences and also held a Ph.D. in physical and mathematical sciences.

His significant contributions include establishing the positron emission tomography (PET) laboratory at the Institute of Human Brain and pioneering a new direction in domestic neuroscience using PET to assess brain organization and activity. He developed methods for diagnosing brain tumors and chronic central nervous system diseases, and his research expanded understanding of neurophysiological mechanisms of attention. He was awarded the I.P. Pavlov Prize in physiology and medicine in 2015.

Other individuals named Medvedev with similar initials exist, such as Sergey Konstantinovich Medvedev (a journalist) and Ilya Dmitrievich Medvedev (son of Dmitry Medvedev), but the academic and scientific context strongly points to Святослав Всеволодович Медведев.
